-- Greek Stocks: Alpha Bank, Ellaktor, Marfin Popular, Sprider Are Active
-- Adam Ewing
-- 2010-07-15T09:40:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/greek-stocks-alpha-bank-ellaktor-marfin-popular-sprider-are-active.html

          
          
             Greece’s  ASE Index  added 22.03, or
1.4 percent, to 1,595.9 at 12:37 p.m. in Athens, its third gain.  
 The  FTSE/ASE 20 Index  of the country’s biggest companies
gained 2.3 percent to 771.6, while the  Cypriot General Market
Index  rose 3.1 percent to 1,190.65.  
 The following shares were among the most active in Athens
trading today. Symbols are in parentheses.  
 Alpha Bank AE  (ALPHA GA) jumped 7.2 percent to 4.93 euros,
its largest rise since June 3. Greek bank stocks rallied after
 Piraeus Bank SA  submitted a proposal to buy “significant
stakes” in Agricultural Bank of Greece SA and Hellenic Postbank
SA.  National Bank of Greece SA  (ETE GA) advanced 5.7 percent to
10.91 euros, gaining for the sixth day.  EFG Eurobank Ergasias SA 
(EUROB GA) rose 7 percent to 4.76 euros.  
 Ellaktor SA  (ELLAKTOR GA) climbed 1.2 percent to 3.33
euros, its sixth rise. Greece’s biggest builder signed a
contract worth 60 million euros ($76.4 million) to build a road
in Bulgaria, according to an e-mailed statement from the Athens-
based company.  
 Marfin Popular Bank Pcl  (MARFB GA) rose 3.1 percent to 1.64
euros. About 10.1 million new shares in the second-biggest
lender on the eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus start
trading today, following a dividend re-investment plan.  
 Sprider Stores SA  (SPRDER GA) advanced 4 percent to 52 euro
cents. The Greek retailer of sportswear and casual clothing will
relocate its Thessaloniki port store after it failed to reach an
agreement on a lower rent for the retail space.  
